[= readme-bytes 0b[2906# Bracket Binary Lisp Bracket Binary Lisp is a lisp-like language written with brackets that can hold sequential binary data. Parenthesis are used for infix math. It's embeddable and useful as a scripting language if you want. ## data Value types are copied. - uint8 uint16 uint32 uint64 int8 int16 int32 int64 - f32 f64 - bool - null - struct Reference types are stored like C++ unique_ptr: - string - binary - function There are three built-in structures: - list - vector - map Vectors are like vectors in C++ and guarantee contigouous memory for value types. Maps are key-value containers with a hash lookup like the dictionary part of a Lua table. ## differences from other lisps There is no garbage collection. Objects on stacks are deallocated when they exit scope unless moved: returned on stack, put into a vector/map, Objects can be persisted by keeping them in closures or returning them in functions. The "main" script called from C++ is itself a function, so all variables are essentially global at that scope. All values are mutable, def and assign are both done via `=` Comments are `//` ## examples ```bbl [= world "world"] [= hello [fn [] [print "Hello, "] [print world] [print "!\n]]] [hello] ``` ```bbl [= file [fopen "file.dat"]] [= binary 07[LOLOLOL]] [file.write 0xabadaba] [file.write binary] ``` ```bbl [struct vertex [f16 x f16 y f16 z]] [= tri [vector vertex [0 1 0]]] [push tri [1 0 0]] [push tri [-1 0 0]] ``` ## control flow ### Loops and infix math: ```bbl [= i 0] [loop (i < 10) [print i "\n"] [= i (i + 1)] ] ``` ### Conditions ```bbl [= choice [get-user-choice]] [cond [(choice == 0) [print "user chose nothing"] ] [(choice == 1) [print "user chose something"] ] [else [print "user chose nothing"] ] ] ``` ## closures ```bbl [= get-content [fn [] [= bytes [read-file "texture.png"]] [fn [] bytes] ]] [= content get-content] [consume-content [content]] ``` ## C++ api It's like Lua in many respects. ```C++ BblState bbl; bbl.exec("script.bbl"); ``` C functions are similar to lua. ```C++ int print(BblState code-quality.md readme.bbl README.md spec.md bbl) {s const char code-quality.md readme.bbl README.md spec.md s; const int i; int arg = 0; while (bbl->hasArg(arg)) { switch (bbl->getArgType(arg)) { case BBL::string: s = bbl->getStringArg(arg); printf(s); break; case BBL::int32: i = bbl->getInt32Arg(arg); printf("%d", i); break; } arg++; } return 0; } BblState bbl; bbl.defn("print", print); bbl.exec("script.bbl"); bbl.exec(); ``` ## file data Large binary data is skipped by file interpreter and lazy loaded when consumed. ```bbl [= png-texture b4096[...]] [load-texture "character-skin" png-texture] // time passes [for uint8 byte in png-texture [emit-byte byte] ] ``` Very easy to include data.]]
